{"type":"assistant.message","data":{"messageId":"9a1dc817-1a97-46ff-a19f-aba7869393fd","content":"Here are the MSBuild evaluation performance issues in this project:\n\n## 1. Recursive Wildcard Glob (line 9, `.csproj`)\n```xml\n<AdditionalFiles Include=\"**\\*.*\" Exclude=\"...\" />\n```\nThe `**\\*.*` pattern forces MSBuild to walk the **entire directory tree** during evaluation. This is one of the most expensive evaluation operations, especially as the repo grows.\n\n## 2. File I/O via Property Function (line 13, `.csproj`)\n```xml\n<BuildNotes>$([System.IO.File]::ReadAllText('build-notes.txt'))</BuildNotes>\n```\nCalling `System.IO.File.ReadAllText` during evaluation performs **synchronous disk I/O** on the evaluation thread. This blocks evaluation and bypasses MSBuild's caching.\n\n## 3. Chained Import Depth (`imports/`)\n```\nlevel1.props → level2.props → level3.props\n```\nA 3-level deep import chain. Each import requires MSBuild to resolve and parse a separate file sequentially. This adds cumulative latency and becomes worse as the chain grows.\n\n---\n\n**Recommendations:**\n- Replace the recursive glob with explicit file lists or narrower patterns.\n- Move file-reading logic to a target (runs at build time, not evaluation time).\n- Flatten the import chain or consolidate into fewer files.","toolRequests":[],"interactionId":"a44a4b88-ca29-4889-b323-a6b156cb99ac","reasoningOpaque":"","reasoningText":"Now I have a complete picture of the project. Let me analyze the MSBuild evaluation performance issues.\n\nThe issues I can identify:\n\n1. **Recursive wildcard glob (`**\\*.*`)** - Line 9 of the .csproj uses `Include=\"**\\*.*\"` which forces MSBuild to walk the entire directory tree during evaluation. This is a well-known performance anti-pattern.\n\n2. **File I/O during evaluation via property function** - Line 13 uses `$([System.IO.File]::ReadAllText('build-notes.txt'))` which performs disk I/O during project evaluation. This blocks the evaluation thread and 